"1343":"1343","1232":"1232","1309":"1309","Drumrany, Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ierland","County Westmeath, Ireland":"County Westmeath, Ierland","of Drumrany, W-Mth, Irln":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ierland","of Drumrany, W-Mth., Irln.":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ierland","Of Drumrany, Westmeath, Irelnd":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ierland","Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ierland","Kildare, County Kildare, Ireland":"Kildare, County Kildare, Ierland"},"en":{"1236–1309":"1236–1309","1232–Male":"1232–Deceased","1256–Male":"1256–Deceased","1258–1343":"1258–1343","1260–Male":"1260–Deceased","1262–Female":"1262–Deceased","1264–Female":"1264–Deceased","1264":"1264","abt 1262":"about 1262","1262":"1262","1260":"1260","abt 1256":"about 1256","ABT 1260":"about 1260","1236":"1236","1258":"1258","ABT 1264":"about 1264","Abt 1255":"about 1255","1256":"1256","1343":"1343","1232":"1232","1309":"1309","Drumrany, Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland","County Westmeath, Ireland":"County Westmeath, Ireland","of Drumrany, W-Mth, Irln":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland","of Drumrany, W-Mth., Irln.":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland","Of Drumrany, Westmeath, Irelnd":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland","Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland","Kildare, County Kildare, Ireland":"Kildare, County Kildare, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fitzgerald","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, Liam, Aidan, Bridgid, Caitlin, Donal, Fitz, Fitzgerald, Ciaran, Colum, Dermot.","Irish: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name <i>Gerald</i> (see   Gerald  ), ‘son of <i>Gerald</i>’. This is a very common Anglo-Norman name in Ireland, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>Mac Gearailt</b>. Irish bearers of the name claim descent from <i>Gerald</i> Fitzwalter de Windsor, constable of Pembroke Castle in the early 12th century, whose grandson Raymond (or Redmond) ‘le Gros’ <i>FitzGerald</i> (died after 1185) led the invasion of Ireland on behalf of Strongbow in 1170. A branch of the family held the title Knight of Glin from at least 1299–2011."],"variants":[{"name":"Jarrell","meanings":["Irish: altered form of   Fitzgerald  .","English (Kent and Middlesex; of Norman origin): variant of <b>Jarrold</b>, itself a variant of   Gerald  ."]},{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"Olivia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["name, first used by  Shakespeare  for the rich heiress wooed by the duke in Twelfth Night (  1599 ). Shakespeare may have taken it as a feminine form of   Oliver   or he may have derived it from Latin <i>oliva</i> ‘olive’. In the 1970s it was particularly associated with the Australian pop singer and actress  Olivia Newton-John  (  b. 1948 ). Since the 1990s it has been very popular throughout the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Olivia Fitzgerald of Kildare was born in 1236, in Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland. She married Lord Henry Dillon about 1255, in Kildare, County Kildare, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1309, in County Westmeath, Ireland, at the age of 73."},"et":{"1236–1309"